{
  "texts": [
    "For discrete data, we generally assume a Dirichlet prior for the parameters which gives rise to the well-established general Bayesian Dirichlet (BD) score which, in its general form, is not score equivalent (Heckerman et al. 1995).",
    "Formally, the general BD score is defined as:",
    "where Γ is the Gamma function, i is the index over the n variables, j is the index over the q i combinations of values of the parents of the node X i, and k is the index over the r i possible values (states) of node X i.",
    "Further, N ijk is the number of instances in the data D where node X i has the kth value, and its parents have the jth combination of values, and",
    "k=1 N ijk representing the total number of instances in the data D where the par- ents of node X i have the jth combination of values."
  ]
}